\emph{p} = 1 (within numerical precision).

\strong{Singular \eqn{\mathbf{W}}}: when parameters are perfectly collinear
(or when \emph{n} is small relative to \emph{p}), \eqn{\mathbf{W}} may be singular.
In that case \code{solve(W)} is replaced by \code{MASS::ginv(W)} (Moore–Penrose
pseudo-inverse) and a warning is issued.  If the pseudo-inverse also fails,
the function returns \code{Inf} with a warning, signalling non-convergence.
